.sh NAME
args \*- copy standard input to argument list and execute
.sh SYNOPSIS
args ...
.sh DESCRIPTION
Args creates an argument list from its argument list and the lines of its standard
input.
Using that argument list it tries to execute a command.
It knows about commands in /bin or /usr/bin, and about command files.
.ti+5
For example,
	find . -type b -a -print | args ls -l
.br
will list all the block special files under your
current working directory.
.sh "SEE ALSO"
pick (I) -- a useful adjunct to args
.sh DIAGNOSTICS
Can't exec -- If the programme cannot be found.
.br
Too many args -- UNIX has a limit of 512 characters in an argument list.
